<FONT SIZE="1" color="#000000" face="Verdana, Arial">
posted April 04, 2001 09:18 AM &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
    &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=edit_post&f=26&t=000040&reply_num=000003&u="><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/edit_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Edit/Delete Post"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=reply&f=26&t=000040&replyto=000003"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/quote_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Reply With Quote"></A>
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Expedience sounds like a nice spell to have for those extra-fast mobs. Sure, I can do damage from a distance with most of my nukes, but it's more mana efficient to let the pet chase the monster down (where training isn't a big problem), letting me save my mana for the next fight. Mages are all about mana efficiency.<P>The pet healing spells are OK for their level, especially the second one which gets pretty mana efficient later on. When your pet just needs a little more life to finish off a mob, a heal is more efficient than summoning a new pet. Where you need a lot more hp, then a good recast is more efficient. Chain-casting isn't a tactic to be poo-pood any more than druid or necro kiting; the mage pet is the most mana efficient DoT spell in the game, not a pet puppy dog. Don't get me wrong, I love Jabartik, but when his time is done, I'll love Kabober and Garn just as much.<P>I don't have a problem with the whole bandages thing. Wizards and enchanters get NO healing capabilities whatsoever. Besides, at lower levels I made a nice little sum of money selling bandages for cheap in dungeons. And since I have no way to cure poison or disease on myself, I still find it handy to carry some bandages around to stabilize my health a bit after a battle. In the lower level undead dungeons, where the cleric wants to try out her anti-undead spells, bandages are a good way to stretch out the mana, as well as letting the tanks build up their bind wound skill on the cheap. For crud's sake, it's a level 4 spell, you shouldn't be surprised that it's not nearly as useful in the post-50 game.<P>Summon Companion is indeed a great idea. I'd rather have it with its little inconveniences than have to do without.
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
